english:
  title: Epitaph for Councillor Yi Gang, Known as Man of Letters
  author: Yi Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My late father, Minister of the Seedbed Pavilion, once presided over the civil examinations in the year of Ding-hai. Many of those he selected became renowned scholars. Councillor Yi, known for his literary refinement, was but fifteen years old, yet his brilliance shone so luminously that all who saw him declared he bore his father's bearing. In later years, his learning deepened and his wisdom grew, so that with each passing day his reputation swelled—a man of towering capacity fit for the highest office.

    When illness befell him, all said, "Surely he shall recover. How could such a man be taken from us?" Yet when death came, they lamented, "Was he born in an inauspicious hour? Did the physicians err in their treatment? How could one so great fall to such an end?" Officials wept for him in the court, kinfolk and companions mourned at his ancestral shrine, and strangers in the street sighed in sorrow. The throne itself, hearing the news, grieved deeply. Lavish gifts were bestowed upon the family, and the Court of Rites was commanded to deliberate upon his posthumous name. The edict read: "Though we do not grant posthumous names to those of the Secret Council rank, we make exception for Yi Gang, for among civil servants of enduring service, there was only Song-su of the Hall of Literature whose loyalty matched his—therefore we do not forget him. In bearing and achievement he is unmatched; now only Gang remains worthy of such honor." When the deliberations were presented, the throne declared: "The name 'Man of Letters and Respect'—only Gang is fit to bear it."

    Alas, the Councillor need have no regrets.

    His friends from Sang-dang, Han Su and Maeng Yun, together with Yeom Heung-bang of Gok-seong, spoke to Yi Saek of Han-san, saying: "Since our friend has passed, who among all people does not grieve? Yet none can escape death's coming. If our friend's memory can be preserved and passed down to others, then we three bear this duty—and in performing it, we might find some solace for our sorrow." Thus they entrusted the epitaph to me, Han Su's calligraphy to record it, Yeom Heung-bang's seal-script to inscribe it, and the carving into stone to their hands. Alas, how can I bear to inscribe the tomb of my own dear friend?

    The Councillor's given name was Gang; his courtesy name was Sa-bi. He was originally named Gang, but changed it to avoid duplication with one of his generation. He was of the Li clan, from Ko-seong. His great-grandfather, Tzon-pi, served as Judge of the Secret Council and Concurrent Inspector, gaining renown in the reign of Kyong-reung. His grandfather Yu held the title Earl of Iron Castle. His father Am served as Councillor and Chief Administrator, with the posthumous title "Man of Literary Refinement," and was famed for calligraphy throughout his age, known as the Master of Apricot Village. His mother, of the Hong clan, was granddaughter to Councillor of Utmost Loyalty Tzu-pan and daughter of Yi Sung-seo, the Right State Counselor.

    First appointed through family merit to the rank of Records Keeper, after passing the examinations he became Vice-Administrator of Kyong-soon Prefecture. Serving in the Bureau of Rites he held the posts of Director and Magistrate; in the Military Bureau, Vice-Chamberlain; in the Imperial Secretariat, Remonstrant; in the Civil Service Bureau, Gentleman of the Robe; in the Treasury Bureau, Vice-Minister. Advancing to the Secret Council, he served as Chief Counselor, Keeper of Records, Scholar-in-Residence, and Vice-Ambassador. Through service in both Inner and Outer Chancelleries he rose to Grand Academician, achieving the rank of Counselor and Court Guardian.

    When the Bright Mausoleum held its lectures at the Royal Academy, he was selected as Royal Tutor. When the throne abdicated, he followed and dwelt in retirement—truly, his resolve was without compromise. In the fifth year of the present reign, Year of the Ram, he was summoned to audience. The throne found him remarkable and at once appointed him Magistrate, entrusting him with the imperial seals. From that time forward he remained ever at the sovereign's side, and the longer he served, the more earnest and reverent he became.

    When advancement came through the Civil Service Bureau, he memorialized the throne: "My lord, to write my own name in the register of promotion—I cannot dare to do this." The throne esteemed him yet more greatly.

    In autumn of the year Hsin-ch'ou, he became Commissioner of Investigation for Kyong-sang Province. At that very time, the northern border suffered invasion and the entire nation retreated southward. When the enemy entered his jurisdiction, the burden of provisioning seemed endless, yet wherever he went, the people received him as though returning to their own homes. The people's spirits revived, and at last the rebellious forces were destroyed—in no small measure through his efforts. Upon his return to the capital, he succeeded Yuan Wen-ding as director of the selection of officials. At that time the reports from the border came without cease, yet through his steady hand both above and below, each received their just recompense and great accomplishments were achieved—much due to his labors.

    When his father passed away, the throne itself ordered that his likeness be painted—an honor shown by the sovereign to great ministers, moving all hearts with admiration. His virtue was indeed magnificent, and surely it was his filial piety that moved Heaven itself. In all affairs he was scrupulous; in friendship he was faithful; in goodness he was ardent; in mind he was impartial. For these reasons was he my friend. Had Heaven granted him longer years to sit in counsel, to resolve great doubts and conduct great affairs—all according to his noble intent—I would have made him my teacher. Yet this was not to be, and my sorrow knows no end.

    His wife was of the Guo clan, daughter of the Judge of Kaesong, surnamed Yon-jun. They had several daughters, all young, and one son born this year. He passed away on the [day omitted] of [month omitted], and was interred on [date omitted] at Blue Village south of the capital, having lived thirty-six years.

    His epitaph reads thus:

    Why grant such complete talent
    Yet withhold the span of years?
    Truly unknowable—Heaven's constancy undefined.
    I carve this epitaph in stone,
    That after a thousand years it sound forth,
    A witness still to the virtue of our Man of Letters.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Seedbed Pavilion' (稼亭) was the epithet of Yi Gang's father, a noted scholar-official.
    - The mention of 'Bright Mausoleum' (聰陵) refers to a king's reign period; serving as Royal Tutor (侍讀) was a prestigious position.
    - '''Northern border invasion'' refers to the Jurchen incursions that plagued late Goryeo period.'
    - The epitaph's final verses express the theme of untimely death—that even great talent cannot escape mortality's decree, and that only through written memorial can such virtue endure.
